<P>
January 17, 1994, Monday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 4; Column 1Q & A; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1113 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ANNE TSUI: PROFESSOR, UCI GRADUATE SCHOOL OF MANAGEMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Susan Christian, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Anne Tsui, a professor in the UCI Graduate School of Management, studies the 
way people interact at the office -- supervisors and subordinates, whites and 
racial minorities, men and women, old and young. In recent research, Tsui 
discovered that today's emphasis on promoting women and minorities has 
alienated another group of people -- white men, who express difficulty in 
adjusting to a diverse workplace. Older people, she says, feel they have been 
left out altogether. Tsui, 45, chats with Times staff writer Susan Christian. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Q: A common assumption might be that minorities experience the greatest level 
of discomfort in a workplace where most of the employees are white. But your 
study says white men, even if in the majority, have a tougher time working with 
minorities and women. 
</P>
<P>
 A: That may seem surprising at first glance. But during the early integration 
of schools and neighborhoods, we found that the opposition came largely from 
the dominant groups. Whites did not like non-whites sharing their neighborhoods 
and classrooms. 
</P>
<P>
 Minority individuals sort of take it for granted that that they are different 
in our society, and over time they have learned to accept it. Perhaps 
minorities have built a greater level of tolerance. 
</P>
<P>
 Q: So minorities are more accustomed to interacting with people of other 
races? 
</P>
<P>
 A: Yes. Furthermore, looking again at integration, being able to move to a 
white neighborhood in some ways is a symbol to minorities that they have 
succeeded. The same is true at the workplace -- minorities' presence in a 
predominantly white population generally means they are better off than if they 
were in an all-minority environment. 
</P>
<P>
 Also, the same can be said regarding women. Historically, women working at 
predominantly female companies -- in the service industry, for example -- have 
lower-paying jobs. So when a woman works for an organization that is 
predominantly male, she generally has a higher level occupation. That suggests 
greater satisfaction with her job. 
</P>
<P>
 Q: Did your study show whether white men are more comfortable with minority 
men or with women at the workplace? In other words, which is the bigger 
discomfort factor -- race or gender? 
</P>
<P>
 A: Gender. Men like being with other men. They have their own culture -- they 
know how to talk to each other, they know how to behave with each other. When a 
female enters their work group, it creates a whole new dynamic, it inhibits 
their camaraderie. So, of course, they feel less comfortable. We all like to be 
ourselves. 
</P>
<P>
 Q: Your study implies that while many companies today are focusing on creating 
an environment sensitive to the concerns of minorities and women, that white 
men are being neglected. 
</P>
<P>
 A: Exactly. Many major companies have programs and projects intended to 
advance the careers of women and minorities. Understandably, the white male is 
wondering, what about me? Jobs and promotions are a scarce resource. The more 
attention that is given to women and minorities, the more fear there is among 
white men that they are not getting equal access to high-level positions.  
</P>
<P>
 Our research suggests that in an effort to remedy past practices that 
disadvantaged women and minorities, we should not ignore the reaction of the 
majority. The sense among white men that they are being neglected is neither 
right or wrong -- these are legitimate, real feelings. 
</P>
<P>
 Q: Yet to some degree, don't companies have to sacrifice some of the interests 
of the majority to further the rights of the minority? If it were left to white 
male supervisors to do the hiring, wouldn't they tend to hire the people they 
feel most comfortable with -- more white males? 
</P>
<P>
 A: It's a natural human tendency to be attracted to those with whom you are 
similar -- whether in race, age, sex, educational level, religion. That 
tendency affects the way we make choices in terms of whom we like to work with. 
So, yes, a diverse workplace is something that companies have to impose upon 
men.  
</P>
<P>
 Q: You mention age. Should age be included more frequently in the diversity 
discussion? 
</P>
<P>
 A: The diversity issue goes well beyond race and gender. People react first 
and foremost to observable differences, and age obviously is an observable 
difference.  
</P>
<P>
 We did a study where we asked supervisors to rate their subordinates. We 
wanted to see if race, gender and age affected the supervisors' judgment. 
</P>
<P>
 Older subordinates underneath young supervisors fared the worst. 
</P>
<P>
 There could be a number of factors involved. Perhaps in some cases the 
subordinate thinks, "I'm older, I'm more experienced" -- and has resentment, so 
doesn't go the extra mile. Still, clearly there is an age bias. 
</P>
<P>
 This issue is particularly important because of the aging baby boom 
generation. We'll soon have a high proportion of older workers. That's going to 
set up a whole different dynamic at the workplace. 
</P>
<P>
 Q: How can companies promote a better understanding among employees in a 
diverse workplace? 
</P>
<P>
 A: Through seminars, programs, management training courses, reading materials. 
Some companies have special celebrations of ethnic holidays and family days. 
All those things can be very useful in getting people from different 
backgrounds to talk to each other and to appreciate differences. 
</P>
<P>
 Also, companies need to do a better job of explaining the qualifications 
necessary for a position so that employees don't make up their own beliefs. 
Often, the white man's reaction is, "She was picked because she is a woman and 
a minority." That's not fair to either person. It's easier to deal with getting 
passed over for a promotion if you understand that the competitor is at least 
as qualified as you. People do not always judge their success by promotions and 
high salaries. They just want equal opportunity. If the decision process is 
fair, people will accept the outcome. The issue of diversity is simply an issue 
of how people treat each other. 
</P>
<P>
 On how employers should deal with the concerns of white men. . . 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't think it's productive for companies to say, 'White males, you 
shouldn't complain because you've had it good for so many years.' " 
</P>
<P>
 On the adaptability of minorities in the workplace. . . 
</P>
<P>
 "Minorities have learned to cope with being different in the working world, 
but white men haven't had much experience in that regard." 
</P>
<P>
 On age bias. . . 
</P>
<P>
 "Older people are a valuable asset to a company. Certainly, young people are 
the source of new ideas. But older people have experience and knowledge of the 
company." 
</P>
<P>
 On her own experience as a minority and as a woman. . . 
</P>
<P>
 "I try to make others feel comfortable with me. The responsibility should not 
always be on the other side to adapt -- we should help each other." 
</P>
</TEXT>
