976 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FILM PARTNERS HAVE NO REGRETS; MOVIES: BARRY LEVINSON AND MARK JOHNSON ARE 
SPLITTING UP, BUT IT DOESN'T MEAN GOODBY FOREVER. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELAINE DUTKA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Hollywood divorces need not be bitter. In moviemaking, as in life, two people 
who've shared a harmonious partnership can wake up one morning with disparate 
needs and goals. 
</P>
<P>
 So it was with the director-producer team of Barry Levinson and Mark Johnson, 
who turned out such hits as "Diner," "Good Morning, Vietnam," and the Academy 
Award-winning "Rain Man." After 10 movies and 12 years, they suggest, the time 
had come to call it quits. 
</P>
<P>
 "I would hate for people to think there's any animosity between us," says 
Johnson, who first met the director when they both worked for Mel Brooks in 
1977. "We're not trying to split things up and see who takes the children. 
We're pleased and relieved. He'll work on his projects. I'll work on mine. And 
we are still working on a number of movies together." 
</P>
<P>
 Thoughts of a breakup began to surface early last spring when the two found 
themselves operating in very different spheres. Johnson was immersed in 
pre-production on "A Perfect World," a project Levinson sidestepped because of 
reservations about the script. Levinson was focused on NBC's police series, 
"Homicide" and writing "Jimmy Hollywood," an upcoming spring release about an 
actor on the fringe of show business, which Johnson and he were shooting for 
Paramount Pictures. 
</P>
<P>
 Because Levinson's voracious directorial appetite left him little time for 
their production company, Baltimore Pictures, Johnson found himself carrying a 
disproportionate amount of the load. 
</P>
<P>
 "As a director, I work fairly constantly," Levinson explains, "so overseeing a 
broad slate of other people's movies became complicated and overwhelming. It 
becomes a question of philosophy: How many things can you -- and do you want to 
-- watch over? Producers are concerned with getting movies made, but that's 
never been my priority. Once you open the door to producing other people's 
projects, you drift away from those you feel passionate about." 
</P>
<P>
 It was only last April that the twosome signed a lucrative three-year, 
non-exclusive deal with Paramount Pictures, which received news of the split 
less than two weeks ago. Though Johnson and Levinson expect to continue 
developing and producing existing projects at the studio, it's still uncertain 
what the future holds. 
</P>
<P>
 "No discussions have taken place," Levinson says. "Given the corporate battle 
(between Viacom Inc. and QVC Network) to take over Paramount Communications, 
I'm sure the studio has more important things on its mind." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Industry insiders place the ball in Paramount's court. "Since the production 
entity with which the deal was signed no longer exists, the deal is null and 
void," says one. "Paramount now has to decide whether it wants to deal with 
each one of them separately -- which might be done on a case-by-case basis. 
From the studio's point of view, the deal wasn't a bad one. They own all the 
projects currently in development and, in less than a year, came away with 
'Jimmy Hollywood' -- a movie they like." 
</P>
<P>
 News of the rupture took the studio by surprise. 
</P>
<P>
 "No one saw it coming," admits one Paramount source. "Barry and Mark seem to 
have the perfect relationship and there doesn't seem to be any hidden agenda. I 
suspect Mark just wants more identity and independence." 
</P>
<P>
 Johnson is currently in pre-production on "The Little Princess," a Warner 
Bros. movie based on Frances Hodgson Burnett's 1905 classic, written by "Fisher 
King's" Richard LaGravanese. He and Levinson will be producing HBO's "Paley," a 
project based on the life of the CBS founder, which will begin shooting in a 
few months, as well as MGM's feature, "Donnie Brasco," the story of an 
undercover FBI agent, which, pending the selection of a director, will get 
under way in the spring. The two also collaborated on "Quiz Show," a project 
based on the Charles Van Doren TV scandal and directed by Robert Redford, which 
is scheduled for release by Hollywood Pictures in September. 
</P>
<P>
 Beyond that, says Johnson -- who reportedly turned down the opportunity to 
head Steven Spielberg's Amblin Entertainment last year -- his plans are 
unclear. 
</P>
<P>
 Levinson is almost set to direct "Disclosure," a Warner Bros. release based on 
Michael Crichton's new novel about a female executive charged with sexual 
harassment at a high-tech company in Seattle. Levinson was called in when 
creative differences arose between Milos Forman and Crichton, who is producing 
the picture himself. Though there are ongoing discussions about what tack to 
take, says the director, the chances of moving ahead "look good." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Says Levinson: "I like suspense, but usually don't want to direct that type of 
film. In this case, however, the male/female dilemma was intriguing. My movies 
generally deal with the inability of men to deal with women and, (by reversing 
the traditional sex roles), Crichton turns the issue of sexual harassment 
around on itself. That's often more effective than exploring it head-on. In the 
'60s, the issue was pushing the nuclear button. The insane 'Dr. Strangelove,' I 
thought, spoke much louder to the topic than an earnest, straightforward drama 
like 'Fail Safe.' " 
</P>
<P>
 Ending the partnership, says Johnson, fills him with "sadness." "I see this as 
a real passing," he says. "I'm leaving behind a part of my youth, my coming to 
maturity as a filmmaker. I'll miss being part of Barry's movies. I don't know 
of anyone as good as he is. I'm certain there will be pangs of jealousy when I 
see some terrific movie he turns out." 
</P>
<P>
 Levinson, who plans to move to Northern California before year's end, delivers 
a less nostalgic, slightly tongue-in-cheek, eulogy. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've been preparing for this for a while now," says the director, "so the 
breakup isn't especially traumatic. It's a conclusion we had to come to. This 
certainly doesn't seem as dramatic as when Martin and Lewis split up. Now, 
that's something that really killed me."  
</P>
</TEXT>
